The children do not only play here, above all they are offered excellent lessons - from basic knowledge to pre-school lessons, and they also learn English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a computer available to the children.
What is more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and so the stress of late picking up the children from a far-away kindergarten is eliminated.
The parents therefore use their working time more productively.
It is no wonder that there is also a development of natural and loyal employer-employee relations.
In this way, Arch.Design joined the Czech companies, which offer significant benefits for the recruitment of new employees, which are family-friendly and through such programs strengthen their human resources marketing.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Look at the interior of Gaudi
The roof is like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn up fish mowers.
This is the Casa Batlló of the Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was called the "Bone House."
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile fragments and mosaics, the facades reminiscent of scales and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of the Art Nouveau style of Antonio Gaudi.
The facade of the house plays with beautiful lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only when you look more closely that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and well-thought-out order.
During the night, the whole facade is even more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination increases the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and intertwined forms also dominate the interior of the house.
Wavy-shaped wood copies the window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even eye holes and bars.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was built by the conversion of a house from 1877, which was carried out by architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but in the end he agreed with Gaudí's idea of an unusual and even cheaper conversion.
The rental house Casa Batlló, however, did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
It was on its zipboard that the decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were his idea.
However, many other artists and artists also worked on the design of the facade.
The joint work on the designs for the Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
As a result, Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's house Casa Milá in the Güell Park, where there are also other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms because of the nickname "Bone House."
Others called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "gagging house."
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a unique central heating system with ventilation channels and typical fireplaces for the time being.
A little bizarre is already the 45-degree inclination.
In his work Gaudí consistently ignored all the construction regulations at the time and was not in any way attached to them.
Before the construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so horrified by the result that they asked for a remedy.
Among other things, the councillors also met with the fact that the construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, there were no more changes, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the city's request to do so, Josep Batlló made an application for the approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was immediately granted to him.
The house owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a social salon, on the third floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
By the basic elements of the change all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for the mutual connection of rooms.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the salon doors and so a larger society could comfortably chat without having to renounce a certain intimacy in more familiar conversations.
The house also received a rather unusual roof and two other floors, with the exception of a new facade.
Gaudí's game with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is disguised and the light courts.
The game of these two colors gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply made use of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The house Casa Batlló, which was added to the World Heritage List of the Unesco in 2005, can today visit anyone.
On the first floor the most spacious and beautiful apartment is made available to the public.
The house owners decided only in the year to take this step and this on the occasion of the 150.birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly profitable business, the visits were kept, and it was also extended to other common and the roof floor rooms, including the roof terrace.
The price for visiting the building monument is not a poplar, it is 16.50 Euro, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
Those who want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with their dragon towers should try to make friends with one of the housekeepers and visit him at home.
