These were the results of the Latinobarómetro survey, which was conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts are particularly in the eye of this year's September and October survey.
First, the good mood in Latin America
and secondly, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In many countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has increased considerably (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing by around 6% a year since 2002, the number of advocates of democracy has increased from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
In Mexico too, where the economy has recovered since the strong fall in last year, such a trend can be seen.
But only half of the people in Mexico and Brazil, the most populous countries in the region, are convinced Democrats, which reduces the regional average (see Figure 2).
About 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country's democratic practice, which is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Figure 3).
About 34% trust the Congress of their country and 45% of their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America's economic crises undermined the efforts for more democracy.
This continued during the world economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America have only experienced a short period of recession and have quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were caught up by a stronger social net.
(According to reports from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America this week, the poverty rate in Latin America increased only slightly in 2009 and fell by 32% this year.)
But there are strong differences in mood from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's strong economy and the popularity of the outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva is reflected in a widespread thinking of progress.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more marked and violent crimes have increased.
It is only for the second time since the start of the survey that many people in Latin America have seen a greater problem in crime in their country than in unemployment (see Figure 5).
About 31% say that either they themselves or a family member have been victims of a crime last year, but compared to 38% last year, the values have fallen and thus reached the lowest level since 1995.
The increase in economic performance is reflected in the increased support for the private and market markets: around 71% of the respondents reported that the private sector is essential for development, and in 2007 it was 56% (see Chart 6).
About 58% said that only the market economy can bring progress to their country, compared with 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela have maintained this view (and 80% are for a private sector), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, nationalized many private companies.
According to 19% of respondents (18% last year), Brazil has the largest weight in the region, followed by the United States (9%, unchanged since last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
The people in Mexico and most of the countries of Central America, on the other hand, see the US as the most influential country, with this role being taken over by Venezuela in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An election doll.
No one had expected the elections to be perfect in Haiti on 28 November.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of the election helpers who hurried to help the troubled country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes, ballot cards in the ringstone, destroyed ballot places and intimidation were only part of the problems.
Electoral facilities opened with hours of delay.
Many Haitians, many of whom had become homeless by the January earthquake, were in search of a choice.
Some finally gave up completely.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some alleged top riders, called for the lifting of the election results due to alleged fraud.
There have been some violent protests throughout the country.
However, Edmond Mulet, head of the UN mission in Haiti, called the election "quite good in many respects."
According to a careful statement by observers of the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, "these irregularities, however serious they may be, do not necessarily invalidate the process."
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which is supposed to be committed to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his candidate, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected final selection is scheduled for January.
There's still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, the rap musician Michel Martelly and the former first-lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidity.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support from the voters, has declared the election to be the winner of the final vote, this could lead to problems.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million earthquake victims still live in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On the day of the election, many Haitians were prevented by a lack of organisation at the vote.
Shortly before the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election were not yet distributed.
There's a lot at stake.
The donor countries see a legitimate, recognised government as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
The Haitians themselves are in the same opinion.
Heavenly in the middle
In the weeks after your husband's sudden death, Argentina's President, Cristina Fernández, experienced a wave of sympathy that drove her popularity rate up by 20 points to over 50%, which is the highest since her election in 2007.
However, whether you will make this a re-election next year depends on whether the clearly grieving Cristina Fernández is more compromise-prepared than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who also led economic policy after his wife's election, often set up budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the president couple to spend the extra revenue on their own initiative.
On paper, the Fernández government lost the majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided and Kirchner's death after a heart attack on October 27 led to further disgust.
Some of the regime critics from the ruling perists stood behind Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic meetings (in which one parliamentarian struck another in the face and others accused the government of bribery) the Congress failed to adopt the budget for 2011.
"I will not discuss it," said the President.
The 2010 budget now also applies for the next year, which gives the President even more opportunity to spend money on his own initiative.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation is currently 11.1%, but many private estimates - and wage demands of the trade unions - have a value of almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took over the office in 2003 when Argentina was shaken by economic crises, declared growth and poverty reduction his main objectives, not the inflation reduction.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, harassed the private sector and cleaned up the National Institute for Statistics and Census, which then enjoyed official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
It has called on the private sector and trade union leaders to talk.
And according to official statements, wage increases will be limited to 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina's agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth surge by a large devaluation in 2002.
For this reason, Cristina Fernández may want to reconnect Argentina with the rest of the world in financial terms.
At the beginning of this year, the government reached an agreement with securities holders who had rejected the country's previous debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández seems to be pushing for an agreement with the Paris Club funders, to whom she owes about $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always rejected a review by the IMF, as is the case elsewhere.
But last month, the Minister for Economic Affairs, Amado Boudou, announced that the Fund will provide "technical support" in the production of a new national consumer price index, and it looks as if this is the first step towards the cleaning up of the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active even without the support of her husband after her term of office.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, which has largely enough of the Kirchnerism.
When the Argentinians return from their summer holiday in March, the wave of sympathy that was brought to her will be turned off.
If she wants to win another election, she has to decide whether to lift many of her husband's political decisions quietly and quietly.
