Arsenic-resistant microbe could allow new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new opportunities for new forms of life on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, it is in their view a sign that life is possible even without the elements previously considered necessary.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow."
"This makes it very special, although it is almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which is published on Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered vital - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But as the scientists found, the bacterium in the California Mono Lake is growing even further, even if it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
"The question is what else is possible," said the co-author of the Ariel D. Anbar report from Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for alien life, as scientists have to recognize life and its forms, Anbar says.
The study deals with microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference, in which no details of the discovery were announced, gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could be about the discovery of alien life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms can start biochemical processes in other planetary systems with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements', which we believe are absolutely vital, are not necessarily defined," said Charles Cockell, Professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that in basic biochemical processes and structures one element can be replaced by another," added Cockell.
This discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Astrobiological Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake due to the high arsenic content.
As arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, it assumed that microbes exposed to both may replace one element with the other.
"The poison of the arsenic is mainly based on the fact that it is chemically similar to phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for the organisms to distinguish one element from the other."
"But the difference is so great that arsenic acts differently than phosphorus. It comes into our biochemical system, where it almost all smears," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
The microbe grows better in phosphorus, but that it can also survive in arsenic, shows that an arsenic-based life form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon, on which arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, a lecturer in microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new, but so far there has been no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early years of the world, she says, so science has assumed that it has used early life forms.
"This gives reason to believe that life can have developed differently than in the early age of the earth," Forster said, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
