On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers or the abolition of the 426 euro support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefit, and the privatisation of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the deputy head of government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former President Felipe González, supports the criticism of the Chancellor Angela Merkel as the responsible person who had evoked the current crisis.
How can these processes be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel's position is not a mistake in her public relations.
On the contrary, this is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany is taking a fundamentally new perspective on the design of our future, which is in conflict with the maintenance of the old traditions of a large part of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, Germany is starting to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first is a strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south should leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German mark - although this is more like science fiction at the moment - is supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a redesign of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macroeconomic control; strict financial management; punishment of the countries that cross the rules; possible termination of some countries' payments and the extension of the cost of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been clear for some time. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission provided incentives for deficits and the German government took out a constitutional reform to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of the gap between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign was made by the Central European country, when Merkel made the decision to save Greece painfully.
At that time, this was strongly criticised, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October Merkel has come out again with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be saved and, at the same time, to require private lenders to bear part of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has driven the Irish crisis and all the following.
But their proposal, although a little sweetened, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be taking part in the reform of the European Union, which will enable these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old functioning of the euro will no longer exist from this date.
2013 will be the year of birth of a new currency area in which the opposing countries are severely punished, can be forced to declare themselves insolvent and, in this case, the private sector must take over part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we must take a hard growth course, with high rates of savings and investment, moderation of consumption, improvement of productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as mentioned by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad not to understand.
It is not just a question of reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to cheat on ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will become more calm.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities we are offered by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero also understood this, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the large companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that, despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis of creating order in his own house has been set in motion.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it does not look like something would change.
Among the options considered, it is not impossible to exclude the fact that we have to leave the euro area that is fully stocked with little serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulatory circumvention
Tricks like that of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show invention spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion of two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed over whether it was an unsporting act or not and whether both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty in the next game against the Auxerre and enter the next game without cards.
In the end, the UEFA disciplinary team punished the club's coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the participating players with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten rules followed in this sport.
Part of the emerging debate about the case is that a team of the football club Real Madrid (who in his hymn pretended to be noble and honour and on other occasions had punished his players for similar events) played the leading role in this, and on the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate is about whether this practice, which is not expressly prohibited by the Statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts are a rule-bypass. In fact, this approach is based on the Statutes of Sports, but seems to be circumventing its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused to the sport spirit should be examined.
The sport spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not at risk by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid that the opposing players have an unjustified benefit from the counter-team.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that they do not correspond to what we normally mean by false play or rule-by-rule, because the avoidance of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a penalty, but should be as conspicuous as possible to be punished by the referee.
The players waited and accepted the penalty joyfully.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders took from the deliberate fouls.
It should be pointed out that the rival was not placed in a more unfavourable position, nor were the benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club does not have these players.
The advantage is that the players will start the next stage of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term advantage, to a certain extent uncertain, as the team could at some point also leave. In addition, the players receive a penalty with this approach and go into the second card cycle, in which they leave less than in the first cycle because of card accumulation with a card.
This is not so clear as to whether this is really an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the sport spirit, which also includes strategic decisions to make the most of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to circumvent a penalty (this would be a clear case of rule-by-law), they wanted to choose when they would be subject to it.
They made a strategic decision to avoid or escape from it without a punishment.
Although the border between the invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of the invention.
I have the impression that the polemics have been caused by two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than more aesthetic.
