Global plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries with a view to achieving a reduction in greenhouse gas (CFCs), which corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction to be implemented in order to stabilise the world's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the step of the concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by the developed countries.
According to the plan put forward yesterday, the main problem in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the CFCs put on the ground due to the lighting would be avoided if the white-burning pears, which still represent a monopoly of 50 to 70% on the market, were replaced by fluorescent or even better, by light-emitting diodes (LED).
The lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
In Copenhagen last year, the large exhaust gas emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, had committed to voluntary reduction plans to reduce global CFC emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it would be necessary to draw 5 Gt from this balance to stabilise the 2 degree Celsius climate increase from today to 2020, in order to prevent it from getting out of control.
In the white-burning pears, 95% of the energy is in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact fluorescent bulbs the energy consumption is reduced by 75%, with the new LED light bulbs one reduces this energy demand again by twice.
The compact fluorescent bulbs hold an average of between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED light bulbs, such as those that the manufacturer of Philips has put on the market this week - this company, by the way, has taken part in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white-burning bulb, which is an indication of the potential savings of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that completely new light bulbs give very little heat, they can also work with a control resistance.
And they don't contain any mercury.
Several specialists have shown that compact fluorescent bulbs have reserves as they contain mercury and that they must be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except for the producers providing a reception point.
According to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact fluorescent bulb, but the coal-fired power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-burning pears.
In the United States alone, these coal-fired power plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury per year.
The report sets out in detail the profits that each country would make through this international programme.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars a year on electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, an equivalent of 3.5 coal-fired power plants, the construction of which would cost Indonesia 2.5 billion.
