But when you look into the detail, things are a little more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Treaty, this money should be "new and additional" in order to ensure that an additional effort has been made without being sufficient to the detriment of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what "new and additional" means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonisation, certain Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the target value that they consider best.
The European Commission, for example, has chosen as a benchmark for those in 2009: international financing is maintained and gives over 150 million in the framework of the "fast-start" financing over three years.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or conditions at the level of ODA.
In return, France considered that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 was "new and additional."
In other words, there are no indicative figures for expenditure in the previous year or at the global level of ODA.
In concrete terms, the total amount of French support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease) - France claims to comply with its commitment to "new and additional" financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule on this yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, have 1 €borrowed as equivalent to 1 €donated.
It is obviously difficult to do this: the effort is not comparable.
If it is possible to justify the use of loans for certain profitable investments (often related to emission-based projects based on the most effective technology), it is deceptive to present the euro that is collected as an equivalent for a donated euro... In addition, only the cost of the loan to the capital country should be counted as a commitment (i.e. the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing other than the following consideration: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by taking up 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% of them (36.1 million euros) - see also the EU document to convince itself.
France is the only country in the EU that is using loans to a large extent.
Germany calls for 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among other things) are 100% committed to donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to fulfil its obligations, France only gives 10 cents and is a similar commitment.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France operates in its fast-start financing with a double flaw: part with a further development of the action over time and part with the reality of the financial use.
France is able to make it believe that it has spent 420 million "new and additional" millions in line with its promises, saving EUR 36.1 million.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once EU-internal (why do the other Member States continue with the donation if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries do not let them completely deceive...
The chapter of early financing only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the whole of discussions on the climate.
But it could be the drop too much in the immense machine of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn its lesson from this first year of early financing.
In the first place, France could announce a change in its way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its obligations and of balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
In particular, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject-matter of long-term financing (another, decisive and currently under discussion): it is not possible to get away from the question of "predictability" or the way in which its loans are held.
France could change its position in order to be as progressive as it is in other matters.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister for the Environment, Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about the rapid start of France and its vision of "predictability" and the use of loans would naturally raise the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - Pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years is taking up 81 different chemical substances, such as a study published this Wednesday by the Génération Futures (former movement for the protection of the rights and respect of coming generations).
The association, which explains that its results "do not represent a statistically significant value in view of the low number of samples analysed, but rather an illustration of the problem being dealt with," had bought the food normally consumed in July and September within four, from a 10-year-old child to the meals, plus an intermediate meal in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three milk products and 1.5 litres of water per day - have been studied by laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is low: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as potentially or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safe carciogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptive factor, according to studies by several institutions, such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if, in the near whole of cases, the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded, it is very well from this survey that the reality in which the consumer is exposed to potentially carcinogenic substances or substances with endocrine disruptive factors is worrying," the association notes.
Even at breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the possibly carcinogenic residues and three of them are certainly known as carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues which may affect the hormone system.
The apple imported from Brazil, as an intermediate meal for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study has found traces of a strictly prohibited insecticide in the EU.
In addition, the hacksteak, the tuna from the box, even the baguette and the gum were fed by pesticides and other chemical substances.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
During dinner, the salmon steak with 34 chemical residues found was "the most rich," and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unloaded.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "is likely to be underestimated," the study said.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "in the light of the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the "increase in civilian diseases."
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables that are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
